WEBVTT

1
00:00:37.500 --> 00:00:40.950
<i>My father hated lawyers all his life.</i>

2
00:00:41.050 --> 00:00:42.750
<i>He wasn't a great guy, my old man.</i>

3
00:00:42.850 --> 00:00:45.200
<i>He drank and beat up my mother.</i>

4
00:00:45.300 --> 00:00:47.050
<i>He beat me up, too.</i>

5
00:00:47.150 --> 00:00:50.850
<i>So you might think I became
a lawyer just to piss him off.</i>

6
00:00:50.950 --> 00:00:53.000
<i>But you'd be wrong.</i>

7
00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:55.700
<i>I've wanted to be a lawyer
ever since I read</i>

8
00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:58.400
<i>about the civil rights lawyers
in the '50s and '60s,</i>

9
00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:00.700
<i>and the amazing uses
they found for the law.</i>

10
00:01:01.300 --> 00:01:04.700
<i>They did what a lot of people
thought was the impossible.</i>

11
00:01:04.850 --> 00:01:07.300
<i>They gave lawyers a good name.</i>

12
00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:10.000
<i>And so I went to law school.</i>

13
00:01:10.100 --> 00:01:11.900
<i>And it did piss my father off,</i>

14
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:13.800
<i>but he was pissed off anyway.</i>

15
00:01:13.900 --> 00:01:15.900
<i>In my first year, he got drunk one day,</i>

16
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.300
<i>fell of a ladder manufactured
by the company he worked for,</i>

17
00:01:19.400 --> 00:01:21.800
<i>and he didn't know who to sue first.</i>

18
00:01:21.900 --> 00:01:24.350
<i>Now, he died a couple of months after that.</i>

19
00:01:26.950 --> 00:01:28.450
<i>Now, some of my classmates,</i>

20
00:01:28.550 --> 00:01:32.000
<i>they knew they were going straight
from school into the top law firms,</i>

21
00:01:32.200 --> 00:01:34.900
<i>thanks mostly to their family connections.</i>

22
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:36.200
<i>Now, the only connections I had</i>

23
00:01:36.300 --> 00:01:38.800
<i>were made in the places
where I tended bar for 3 years,</i>

24
00:01:38.900 --> 00:01:40.050
<i>so I could pay my tuition.</i>

25
00:01:40.150 --> 00:01:41.950
<i>And while I still had plans</i>

26
00:01:42.050 --> 00:01:44.650
<i>to shine the blazing light of justice
into every dark corner,</i>

27
00:01:44.750 --> 00:01:47.550
<i>what I really needed right now was a job.</i>

28
00:01:47.650 --> 00:01:48.700
<i>And badly.</i>

29
00:01:48.800 --> 00:01:51.450
<i>Because there are too many
lawyers in Memphis.</i>

30
00:01:55.200 --> 00:01:57.700
<i>This city's infested with them.</i>

31
00:02:01.900 --> 00:02:03.600
I don't think so.

32
00:02:03.700 --> 00:02:06.600
<i>I can't think of anything more embarrassing...</i>

33
00:02:06.700 --> 00:02:07.850
- No.
- <i>...than telling people...</i>

34
00:02:07.950 --> 00:02:10.200
<i>...I work for a guy like Bruiser Stone.</i>

35
00:02:10.300 --> 00:02:11.500
Negative.

36
00:02:12.950 --> 00:02:16.950
<i>I mean, he's a lawyer,
and they call him Bruiser.</i>

37
00:02:17.050 --> 00:02:19.650
<i>That's how desperate I am.</i>

38
00:02:19.750 --> 00:02:20.650
Sure.

39
00:02:20.750 --> 00:02:22.650
Shut the door.

40
00:02:22.750 --> 00:02:25.600
No, not that. Not that either.

41
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Sure.

42
00:02:28.450 --> 00:02:29.350
Sure.

43
00:02:29.450 --> 00:02:32.250
Let's make it... Let's make it my house.

44
00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:35.000
Okay.

45
00:02:36.050 --> 00:02:38.500
I really pity the poor FBI technician

46
00:02:38.600 --> 00:02:41.800
that's gonna have to extract
the data from that conversation.

47
00:02:41.900 --> 00:02:44.100
Live sharks in a lawyer's office.

48
00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:46.100
It's a joke. Get it?

49
00:02:46.200 --> 00:02:47.800
So, Prince,

50
00:02:47.900 --> 00:02:49.700
is this the law student
you were telling me about?

51
00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:52.750
Yes, sir. I just finished my third year
at Memphis state.

52
00:02:52.850 --> 00:02:54.300
Couldn't you use him around here?

53
00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:56.300
Look, I'll vouch for him.

54
00:02:56.400 --> 00:02:57.800
The boy needs a job.

55
00:02:57.900 --> 00:03:01.500
He's tended bar at our clubs.

56
00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:04.700
This'll be a great place
for you to work, Rudy.

57
00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:06.400
This'll be...

58
00:03:06.500 --> 00:03:08.300
...a great place for you to work.

59
00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:10.900
You can see what real lawyers do.

60
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.150
Now, it ain't exactly a salaried position.

61
00:03:14.250 --> 00:03:15.300
It isn't?

62
00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:19.100
I expect my associates
to pay for themselves,

63
00:03:19.200 --> 00:03:22.250
generate their own fees.

64
00:03:22.350 --> 00:03:23.700
Talk to me.

65
00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:26.050
How exactly does that work?

66
00:03:26.150 --> 00:03:29.150
Well, Rudy, you draw $1,000 a month,

67
00:03:29.250 --> 00:03:32.150
and you get to keep one third
of all the fees that you generate.

68
00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:36.200
Now, if you can't cover your draw
at the end of each month,

69
00:03:36.300 --> 00:03:37.500
you owe me the balance.

70
00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:39.550
Do you understand?

71
00:03:39.650 --> 00:03:41.300
Sounds fair to me, Rudy.

72
00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:43.100
And that's a hell of a deal, really.

73
00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:45.200
You can make a lot of money this way.

74
00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:47.900
I'll tell you something, Rudy.

75
00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:49.700
That's the only way I operate.

76
00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:51.400
And I'll get you a lot of good cases.

77
00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:54.250
I have cases.

78
00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:58.350
I have two cases right now.

79
00:03:58.450 --> 00:04:01.450
One is a will that I'm drafting
for an old woman.

80
00:04:01.550 --> 00:04:03.150
She's loaded, too. She's worth millions.

81
00:04:03.250 --> 00:04:05.250
And then I have this other case.

82
00:04:05.350 --> 00:04:06.500
It's an insurance case.

83
00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:09.700
Great Benefit. You heard of 'em.

84
00:04:09.800 --> 00:04:11.900
You got these clients signed?

85
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.100
I'm on my way to see 'em right now.

86
00:04:14.200 --> 00:04:15.800
And they'll listen to me, too.

87
00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:17.500
I helped 'em over at a law workshop.

88
00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:19.200
All right, I'm gonna have you talk to

89
00:04:19.300 --> 00:04:21.100
an associate of mine, Deck Schifflet.

90
00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:24.700
He used to work with these
big insurance companies.

91
00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:27.550
He handles all the high-powered
stuff around here.

92
00:04:27.650 --> 00:04:30.000
Hey, Deck!

93
00:04:30.100 --> 00:04:32.250
Deck! Damn it.

94
00:04:32.350 --> 00:04:33.750
You got the paperwork on this stuff?

95
00:04:33.850 --> 00:04:35.850
- In my car.
- Good.

96
00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:41.750
Hey, good lookin'!

97
00:04:41.850 --> 00:04:44.450
This is Deck Schifflet.

98
00:04:44.550 --> 00:04:47.000
This man will get you plugged in.

99
00:04:47.100 --> 00:04:48.600
What I want you to do,

100
00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:51.350
I want you to draw up a lawsuit
against this Great Benefit,

101
00:04:51.450 --> 00:04:54.150
and you put my name on it.

102
00:04:54.250 --> 00:04:55.950
We're gonna file it today.

103
00:04:56.050 --> 00:04:57.350
Thank you.

104
00:04:57.450 --> 00:04:59.450
Rudy, you're gonna learn a lot.

105
00:04:59.550 --> 00:05:02.100
Rudy, I'm glad you came here.

106
00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:04.100
You're making good choices already, son.

107
00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:05.300
All right, well, thank you.

108
00:05:05.400 --> 00:05:06.900
- Okay, thank you.
- I appreciate it.

109
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:08.600
Close the door on your way out now, okay?

110
00:05:08.700 --> 00:05:10.300
Law offices. May I help you?

111
00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:11.800
This is an office, there's people in it.

112
00:05:11.900 --> 00:05:14.300
If there's somebody in the office,
you can't have it, it's off limits.

113
00:05:14.400 --> 00:05:15.750
This is the bathroom.

114
00:05:15.850 --> 00:05:18.000
- Just a minute.
- Sorry.

115
00:05:18.300 --> 00:05:20.150
So, are you an associate here?

116
00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:21.750
Sort of. Not really.

117
00:05:21.850 --> 00:05:23.200
I'm actually not a lawyer yet.

118
00:05:23.300 --> 00:05:27.350
Bruiser usually asks me to review
the insurance cases when they come in.

119
00:05:27.450 --> 00:05:29.800
I used to work for specific
mutual insurance company.

120
00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:31.500
I got sick of that. I went to law school.

121
00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:33.900
Well, when did you finish law school?

122
00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:35.200
5 years ago.

123
00:05:35.300 --> 00:05:37.700
See, I'm having a little trouble
with the bar exam.

124
00:05:37.800 --> 00:05:39.800
I sat for it 6 times.

125
00:05:39.900 --> 00:05:41.800
- I'm sorry to hear that.
- Yeah. When do you take yours?

126
00:05:41.900 --> 00:05:43.800
- I take it in, like, 3 weeks.
- Oh, yeah.

127
00:05:43.900 --> 00:05:46.250
- It's that hard?
- Pretty rough, I'll say.

128
00:05:46.350 --> 00:05:47.500
I took it a year ago.

129
00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:49.100
I don't think I'm gonna take it again.

130
00:05:49.200 --> 00:05:51.050
Anyway, this is Bruiser's law library.

131
00:05:51.150 --> 00:05:53.400
If you want to get anything out of the fridge

132
00:05:53.500 --> 00:05:56.200
or use the fridge, you can
put your name on stuff.

133
00:05:56.300 --> 00:05:58.900
They'll eat it anyway. Put that in for me.

134
00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:00.400
It's only rice. What the hell.

135
00:06:00.500 --> 00:06:01.650
- Daisy!
- Yeah.

136
00:06:01.750 --> 00:06:03.450
We made a mess here.
Get that up, huh?

137
00:06:03.550 --> 00:06:05.400
- Sure, deck.
- Anyway...

138
00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:07.900
So wait, what happens
when you have to go to court?

139
00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:10.100
I've actually gone a few times myself.

140
00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:11.150
I haven't gotten caught.

141
00:06:11.250 --> 00:06:14.800
There's so many lawyers here,
it's impossible to keep up with us.

142
00:06:16.450 --> 00:06:18.300
Bruiser owns all this.

143
00:06:18.400 --> 00:06:20.900
Oh! Nice!

144
00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:22.350
You can't call it a firm exactly.

145
00:06:22.450 --> 00:06:24.450
It's every man for himself.

146
00:06:24.550 --> 00:06:25.950
You'll learn.

147
00:06:28.350 --> 00:06:30.250
What, are you moving?

148
00:06:30.350 --> 00:06:31.950
Evicted.

149
00:06:33.750 --> 00:06:35.550
Here's the policy.

150
00:06:38.550 --> 00:06:39.550
What do you think?

151
00:06:39.650 --> 00:06:43.100
Well, this is the scratch-and-sniff
armpit of the industry.

152
00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:44.950
What are their grounds for denial?

153
00:06:45.050 --> 00:06:46.000
Oh, well, everything.

154
00:06:46.100 --> 00:06:48.950
They first denied it just on principle,

155
00:06:49.050 --> 00:06:53.150
and then they said that leukemia
was a pre-existing condition,

156
00:06:53.250 --> 00:06:56.000
and then they said leukemia
wasn't covered in the policy.

157
00:06:56.100 --> 00:06:57.350
I got 7 letters here.

158
00:06:57.450 --> 00:06:59.450
Have all the premiums been paid?

159
00:06:59.550 --> 00:07:01.950
According to Miss Black,
she paid every single one of them.

160
00:07:02.050 --> 00:07:03.550
They're bastards!

161
00:07:03.650 --> 00:07:07.400
This is a typical debit insurance scam.

162
00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:09.850
The Blacks call it street-surance.

163
00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:12.700
So what do I do?

164
00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:16.100
You sign 'em up. Sign 'em all up.

165
00:07:16.200 --> 00:07:18.350
To J. Lyman Stone.

166
00:07:18.450 --> 00:07:20.000
- All right.
- Yeah.

167
00:07:20.100 --> 00:07:22.050
I'll help you on this one.

168
00:07:22.150 --> 00:07:24.400
All right. Well, thank you. I appreciate it.

169
00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:26.050
There's nothing more thrilling

170
00:07:26.150 --> 00:07:29.300
than nailing an insurance company.

171
00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:49.300
Hi, Mrs. Black. It's Rudy Baylor.

172
00:07:49.400 --> 00:07:53.050
Remember? I'm handling
your case against Great Benefit.

173
00:07:53.150 --> 00:07:56.750
I met you over at the Memphis
state law workshop.

174
00:07:56.850 --> 00:07:58.050
Well, come in.

175
00:07:58.150 --> 00:08:01.550
Come in. I'm sorry about them crazy dogs.

176
00:08:01.650 --> 00:08:02.950
Oh, that's okay.

177
00:08:03.050 --> 00:08:05.050
I thought you was a Jehovah's witness.

178
00:08:05.150 --> 00:08:07.800
- Where's Buddy?
- He's out in the car.

179
00:08:07.900 --> 00:08:10.150
Where's he going?

180
00:08:10.250 --> 00:08:12.250
Buddy isn't going nowhere.

181
00:08:12.350 --> 00:08:15.000
He ain't right in the head.
War injury. Korea.

182
00:08:15.150 --> 00:08:18.250
You know them metal detectors
at the airport?

183
00:08:18.350 --> 00:08:20.250
He can walk through one buck naked,

184
00:08:20.350 --> 00:08:21.550
and the thing would go off.

185
00:08:21.650 --> 00:08:23.850
He's got a plate in his head.

186
00:08:23.950 --> 00:08:25.650
Oh!

187
00:08:25.750 --> 00:08:28.150
That's awful.

188
00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
How's Donny Ray?

189
00:08:32.100 --> 00:08:34.000
Well, good days and bad.

190
00:08:34.100 --> 00:08:35.650
"Plate in head."

191
00:08:35.750 --> 00:08:36.750
You want to meet him?

192
00:08:36.850 --> 00:08:38.250
Maybe later.

193
00:08:38.350 --> 00:08:39.950
Now...

194
00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:47.500
Great Benefit first denied
your claim last August

195
00:08:47.600 --> 00:08:50.000
when Donny Ray was diagnosed.

196
00:08:50.100 --> 00:08:52.950
Why'd y'all wait till now to consult a lawyer?

197
00:08:53.050 --> 00:08:55.150
Stupid, I guess.

198
00:08:55.250 --> 00:08:56.650
I just kept writing 'em,

199
00:08:56.750 --> 00:08:58.600
and they kept writing me back,

200
00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:01.400
and this here's the latest one.

201
00:09:03.550 --> 00:09:04.950
"Dear Mrs. Black,

202
00:09:05.050 --> 00:09:08.250
"on 7 prior occasions the company
has denied your claim in writing.

203
00:09:08.350 --> 00:09:11.200
"We now deny it for the 8th and final time.

204
00:09:11.300 --> 00:09:15.000
"You must be stupid, stupid, stupid.

205
00:09:16.250 --> 00:09:23.050
"Sincerely, Everett Lufkin,
Vice President of Claims."

206
00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:27.000
I don't believe this.

207
00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:29.500
You're the lawyer.

208
00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:33.750
Mom says nice things about you.

209
00:09:35.850 --> 00:09:39.750
She says you're suing those bastards
over at Great Benefit.

210
00:09:40.050 --> 00:09:42.000
Gonna make 'em pay, huh?

211
00:09:42.100 --> 00:09:45.000
That's right. That's right.

212
00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:48.000
- Hi, mama.
- Hi, honey.

213
00:09:48.100 --> 00:09:51.050
Well, before we can file a claim,

214
00:09:51.150 --> 00:09:53.300
I need all three of you to sign this.

215
00:09:53.400 --> 00:09:55.550
Is daddy comin' in?

216
00:09:55.650 --> 00:09:58.000
Well, he said he wasn't.

217
00:09:58.100 --> 00:10:00.750
Some days he comes in,
and some days he don't.

218
00:10:00.850 --> 00:10:02.000
Well, this is a contract.

219
00:10:02.100 --> 00:10:03.800
What's in it?

220
00:10:03.900 --> 00:10:05.550
Oh, the usual.

221
00:10:05.650 --> 00:10:07.200
It's standard language.

222
00:10:07.300 --> 00:10:08.400
It basically says that

223
00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:11.000
y'all hire us to be your attorneys,

224
00:10:11.100 --> 00:10:12.900
and we take care of the case for you.

225
00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.500
We handle any expenses
that we might have,

226
00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:17.850
and then we get one third of any recovery.

227
00:10:19.550 --> 00:10:23.350
Well, why does it take
two pages to say all that?

228
00:10:23.450 --> 00:10:25.050
Don't light that.

229
00:10:26.100 --> 00:10:28.750
No wonder I'm dying.

230
00:10:30.100 --> 00:10:32.500
And all three of us have to sign it?

231
00:10:32.600 --> 00:10:35.000
Yes, ma'am, all three.
Just where your name is.

232
00:10:35.100 --> 00:10:37.050
Well, he said he wasn't coming in.

233
00:10:37.150 --> 00:10:40.350
Take the pen and go out there
and make him sign the damn thing.

234
00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:42.500
I guess I could.

235
00:10:49.400 --> 00:10:52.350
Now, Buddy, you gotta sign this paper,

236
00:10:52.450 --> 00:10:55.050
so Donny Ray can get
that operation he needs,

237
00:10:55.150 --> 00:10:57.450
and I don't want no trouble out of you.

238
00:10:57.550 --> 00:10:59.400
I'll take that damn bottle

239
00:10:59.500 --> 00:11:01.400
and throw it across Union street.

240
00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:04.500
Now, sign the damn thing.
Come on, hurry up.

241
00:11:06.350 --> 00:11:09.350
I know you must think they're crazy.

242
00:11:10.850 --> 00:11:12.900
They're nice folks.

243
00:11:17.450 --> 00:11:19.400
Hey, man.

244
00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:24.500
Hey, your nose is bleedin'.

245
00:11:26.050 --> 00:11:27.800
Mrs. Black!

246
00:11:27.900 --> 00:11:29.100
Hold your head up.

247
00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:31.250
Mrs. Black!

248
00:11:31.350 --> 00:11:33.000
- All right, all right.
- It's okay. I got it.

249
00:11:33.100 --> 00:11:34.300
He's bleedin'.

250
00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:36.250
Put your head back.
Put your head back. Come on.

251
00:11:36.350 --> 00:11:37.950
Come on, put it back.

252
00:11:38.050 --> 00:11:40.450
Oh, sweetie, okay. It'll be all right.

253
00:11:41.900 --> 00:11:44.600
I got it. I got it.

254
00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:47.450
Okay, okay.

255
00:11:47.550 --> 00:11:49.050
Okay, I got it.

256
00:11:49.150 --> 00:11:51.450
